[[File:Fossa Corbulonis map.png|right|thumb|Map of the coast in Roman times superimposed on [[South Holland]] today, showing Praetorium Agrippinae's location.]]
{{one source|date=February 2013}}
'''Praetorium Agrippinae''' was a Roman army encampment (Lat.: ''[[castellum]]'') in modern-day [[Valkenburg, South Holland|Valkenburg]], [[Netherlands]].<ref>See the [[Tabula Peutingeriana]], section II and De Hing & Vos (2005).</ref> It was situated strategically on the [[Oude Rijn (Utrecht and South Holland)|Oude Rijn]] between the ''castella'' of [[Matilo]] in the east and [[Lugdunum Batavorum]] to the west, in the area belonging the [[Cananefates]].<ref>De Hing & Vos (2005) 80.</ref> As part of the [[limes|Roman border system]] (Lat.: ''[[limes]]''), more specifically the [[Germanic Limes|Lower Germanic ''Limes'']], it played a vital role in keeping the [[Frisii]] to the north at bay.<ref>De Hing & Vos (2005) 83.</ref>

==History==
[[File:Valkenburg - N206 - Romeinse weg.jpg|thumb|left|The old [[roman road]] at [[Valkenburg, South Holland|Valkenburg]] today.]]
[[Roman emperor]] [[Caligula]] had the first ''castellum'' built in [[39]] or [[40]] AD, although [[roman currency|coins]] and pottery (''[[terra sigillata]]'') found at the site suggest an army division may have been stationed there before its construction.<ref>De Hing & Vos (2005) 83.</ref> Caligula named the encampment after his mother, [[Agrippina the Elder|Vipsania Agrippina]], and might have been present at its completion.<ref>De Hing & Vos (2005) 91. See also: Lendering, J. [http://www.livius.org/ga-gh/germania/praetorium_agripinnae.html ''Praetorium Agrippinae (Valkenburg)''].</ref>
The fortifications surrounding the camp at this stage consisted of a [[palisade]]d earthen wall and three [[moats]]. Originally two [[Maniple (military unit)|maniples]] (or four ''[[centuriae]]'') of [[legionaries]] and two ''[[turmae]]'' of cavalry had been stationed at the fort.<ref>De Hing & Vos (2005) 107.</ref> After the [[Revolt of the Batavi]] ([[69]]-[[70]] AD) however, when the local tribes had razed the fortress to the ground, the entire [[List of Roman auxiliary regiments|''cohors IV Thracum'']] relocated here.

At around [[120]] AD a village developed along the [[Roman roads#Types of roads|''via militaris'']] just south of it, where archaeological investigation has recently uncovered the remains ofstorehouses and granaries (''[[horrea]]'').
The Romans erected a large stone fort in about [[180]] AD, which they subsequently abandoned somewhere between [[240]] and [[275]] AD.
During [[Constantius I Chlorus]]' reign the old ''castellum'' was rebuilt and converted into a granary, holding supplies for the roman province of [[Brittannia]].

